TITLE: Incorrect Class Concatenation
DESCRIPTION: Illustrates that direct concatenation of class names from useClasses can lead to duplicated classes and unpredictable styling. It is crucial to use mergeClasses for correct class merging.
SOURCE: https://github.com/microsoft/fluentui/blob/master/docs/react-v9/contributing/rfcs/react-components/styles-handbook.md#2025-04-20_snippet_8

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
import { makeStyles, mergeClasses } from '@griffel/react';

const useClasses = makeStyles({
  rootA: { display: 'flex' },
  rootB: { display: 'grid' },
});

function App(props) {
  const classes = useClasses();

  // âœ… Returns "class-display-grid"
  const correctClasses = mergeClasses(classes.rootA, classes.rootB);
  // ðŸ”´ Never concatenate class strings, returns "class-display-flex class-display-grid"
  const wrongClasses = classes.rootA + ' ' + classes.rootB;
}
```

